Part 3

Rohan took the body back to Odisha.

The office had sent a private ambulance, the white Ambassador kind, the driver wearing the company uniform with the grey epaulettes on the shoulders.

Rohan didn't speak to Adarsh.

He stood near the casualty counter, signed the release forms, his signature neat and clear — the signature he had learned after Vikram left.

His hand didn't tremble today.

The red Nandyal dust had gone from his shoes, replaced by polished black leather that reflected the hospital corridor lights.

Ananya and Sarita left in the evening.

They had the Howrah train tickets.

"Come to Bagbazar, Dr. Tripathy," Sarita said at the gate.

"The neem trees are green now."

"I will come," Adarsh said.

He watched the auto rickshaw carry them toward the station.

Ananya was sitting in the back, the three-legged wooden horse kept on her lap, her hand holding the green ledger.

She didn't look back.

---

Adarsh returned to his room at eight.

The room was small, smelling of old paper and the tea he had left unfinished on the table.

He went to the cupboard.

He opened the lowest shelf, behind the old medical journals and the files of forgotten cases.

The pathology textbook was still there.

He pulled it out.

The cover was grey with the dust of twenty-two years, the corners frayed, the cardboard showing through the paper.

He opened it.

Chapter three. *Hepatic cirrhosis.*

The line was still there, the blue ink of Vicky's pen dry and faded, ending mid-sentence near the margin.

*Decompensated liver function is marked by portal hypertension...*

He closed the book.

He kept it on the table near his stethoscope.

Vikram had left the room.

He had left the white coat.

He had left the fourteen hundred crore.

He had left the seventy-six hundred crore.

Most people who wrote his obituary in the business weekly would write about the empire he had surrendered.

They would call him a loser.

A tycoon who couldn't keep his grip on the wheel.

A success that had gone soft at the end.

Adarsh walked to the window.

The hospital lights below were yellow, shining on the wet asphalt of the M.G. Road.

The auto rickshaws honked. The vendors shouted. The city went on.

But as he looked at his own white apron hanging on the wall, the blue thread stitching on the pocket — *Adarsh Tripathy* — still neat and clear after thirty years, he wondered.

Who is the loser?

He?

Or we, who sit in our comfortable chairs, making comfortable decisions, holding onto our names until the name is the only thing left of us?

He had no answer.

The book on the table was closed.

The window was dark.

And the story of Vikram Ahuja had ended exactly where it began — on a wooden bench, under the shadow of a neem tree, with a glass of red tea that had gone cold in the wind.

[End of Novel]
